    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="1307"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1307">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.77/127.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 30, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received, and has communicated
                    to the Secretary of War, your No. 1369, of the 19th instant, transmitting a
                    joint letter from Messrs. T. K. Eccles and J. F. Ealy, representatives,
                    respectively, of the Order of Railway Conductors and the Brotherhood of
                    Locomotive Engineers, with relation to some six hundred engineers and conductors
                    who have left the service of the National Railways of Mexico, stating that,
                    should the services of these men be needed by the United States in handling
                    troop trains in the Republic of Mexico, the organizations mentioned would be
                    able to furnish all the men needed, who would be thoroughly familiar with the
                    tracks over which the trains would be run.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
